              <Glosses>
                <Gloss>neck</Gloss>
              </Glosses>
              <Comments>τράχηλος also occurs in the NT in certain idiomatic expressions, for example, ‘to fall on the neck of someone’ ({S:04201502000050} and {S:04402003700020}) in the sense of ‘to embrace’ ({D:34.64}), and ‘to put down their necks’ ({S:04501600400016}) meaning ‘to risk their lives’ ({D:21.8}). It is rare indeed that one can translate such idioms literally, since ‘to fall on the neck of someone’ may readily suggest a murderous attack, and ‘to risk one’s neck’ may be simply meaningless, since the custom of beheading as a means of execution may be relatively unknown.</Comments>
            </LEXSense>
